data.enText: swung
swung

data.chText: 摆动
data.enText: hang and move

data.chText: （使）摆动，摇摆，摇荡
data.enText: to move backwards or forwards or from side to side while hanging from a fixed point; to make sth do this

data.chText: 他边走边摆着双臂。
data.enText: His arms swung as he walked.

data.chText: 她腰带上挂着的一串钥匙摆来摆去。
data.enText: A set of keys swung from her belt.

data.chText: 随着他推她，她在秋千上越荡越高。
data.enText: As he pushed her, she swung higher and higher (= while sitting on a swing) .

data.chText: 他坐在凳子上晃动着两条腿。
data.enText: He sat on the stool, swinging his legs.

data.chText: 纵身跃向；荡向；悬吊到
data.enText: to move from one place to another by holding sth that is fixed and pulling yourself along, up, etc.

data.chText: 他纵身跳下车。
data.enText: He swung himself out of the car.

data.chText: 枪声一响，猴子纷纷在树丛中飞跃荡走。
data.enText: The gunshot sent monkeys swinging away through the trees.

data.chText: 弧线运动
data.enText: move in curve

data.chText: （使）弧线运动，转弯，转动
data.enText: to move or make sth move with a wide curved movement

data.chText: 一队汽车拐出了宫门。
data.enText: A line of cars swung out of the palace gates.

data.chText: 他把两腿移过来放下床。
data.enText: He swung his legs over the side of the bed.

data.chText: 门开了。
data.enText: The door swung open.

data.chText: 她把门推开。
data.enText: She swung the door open.

data.chText: 迅速转向
data.enText: turn quickly

data.chText: （使）突然转向，突然转身
data.enText: to turn or change direction suddenly; to make sth do this

data.chText: 公共汽车猛地拐向左边。
data.enText: The bus swung sharply to the left.

data.chText: 他猛地将照相机转了个方向对着反面。
data.enText: He swung the camera around to face the opposite direction.

data.chText: 试图击中
data.enText: try to hit

data.chText: （挥动某物）朝…打去
data.enText: to try to hit sb/sth

data.chText: 她挥着铁棍朝我打来。
data.enText: She swung at me with the iron bar.

data.chText: 他朝着我这边又挥了一拳。
data.enText: He swung another punch in my direction.

data.chText: 改变意见 / 情绪
data.enText: change opinion/mood

data.chText: （使）改变（意见、情绪等）
data.enText: to change or make sb/sth change from one opinion, mood, etc. to another

data.chText: 这个州原先支持共和党，现在倒向了民主党。
data.enText: The state has swung from Republican to Democrat.

data.chText: 他时而害怕，时而好奇。
data.enText: His emotions swung between fear and curiosity.

data.chText: 这场比赛胜负未卜。
data.enText: The game could swing either way (= either side could win it) .

data.chText: 我设法使他们转而接受了我的观点。
data.enText: I managed to swing them round to my point of view.

data.chText: 做；获得
data.enText: do/get sth

data.chText: （有时略微不正当地）获得，搞到，办成
data.enText: to succeed in getting or achieving sth, sometimes in a slightly dishonest way

data.chText: 我们正在想法子，好坐上同一个航班。
data.enText: We're trying to swing it so that we can travel on the same flight.

data.chText: 你有没有可能帮我们弄几张票？

data.enText: Is there any chance of you swinging us a couple of tickets?

data.enText: to have a strong rhythm

data.enText: to pretend to be ill/sick when in fact you are not, especially to avoid work

data.chText: 我认为她没有什么病，只不过是在装病偷懒而已。
data.enText: I don't think there's anything wrong with her─she's just swinging the lead.

data.chText: lead是船靠近陆地时水手测量水深用的水铊。swinging the lead被认为是件轻松的工作，逐渐变成“逃避干重活”的意思。
data.enText: The lead was a weight at the bottom of a line that sailors used to measure how deep water was when the ship was near land. ‘Swinging the lead’ was thought to be an easy task, and came to mean avoiding hard work.

data.enText: to visit a place or person for a short time

data.chText: 下班回家路过时我要到你家来一下。
data.enText: I'll swing by your house on the way home from work.

data.chText: 投票显示10%的人转而支持工党。

ex.enText: She felt sick as the waves rocked the boat from side to side.

ex.chText: 他把儿子抱在怀里轻轻摇晃。

ex.chText: 树枝在微风中轻轻摆动。
ex.enText: The branches swayed gently in the breeze.

ex.chText: 那个虚弱的男孩子摇晃着倒下了。

tr: changing location by moving back and forth
a square dance figure
a pair of dancers join hands and dance around a point between them
in baseball
a batter's attempt to hit a pitched ball
example: he took a vicious cut at the ball

tr: the act of swinging a golf club at a golf ball and (usually) hitting it
a sweeping blow or stroke
example: he took a wild swing at my head

tr: mechanical device used as a plaything to support someone swinging back and forth
a jaunty rhythm in music
a style of jazz played by big bands popular in the 1930s
flowing rhythms but less complex than later styles of jazz
a state of steady vigorous action that is characteristic of an activity
example: the party went with a swing
it took time to get into the swing of things

tr: alternate dramatically between high and low values
example: the market is swinging up and down

tr: hit or aim at with a sweeping arm movement
example: The soccer player began to swing at the referee

tr: engage freely in promiscuous sex, often with the husband or wife of one's friends
example: There were many swinging couples in the 1960's

tr: make a big sweeping gesture or movement
play with a subtle and intuitively felt sense of rhythm
move or walk in a swinging or swaying manner
change direction with a swinging motion
turn
move in a curve or arc, usually with the intent of hitting
be a social swinger
socialize a lot
influence decisively
example: This action swung many votes over to his side

tr: live in a lively, modern, and relaxed style
example: The Woodstock generation attempted to swing freely

tr: hang freely
example: the ornaments dangled from the tree
The light dropped from the ceiling

tr: have a certain musical rhythm

value.def: If something swings or if you swing it, it moves repeatedly backwards and forwards or from side to side from a fixed point.

example.ex: The sail of the little boat swung crazily from one side to the other...
example.tran: 小船的帆猛烈地左右摇摆着。

example.ex: She was swinging a bottle of wine by its neck...
example.tran: 她正握着瓶颈摇晃一瓶葡萄酒。

example.ex: Ian lit a cigarette and sat on the end of the table, one leg swinging.
example.tran: 伊恩点燃了一支烟，坐在桌子的一端，一条腿晃来晃去。

example.ex: ...a woman in a tight red dress, walking with a slight swing to her hips.
example.tran: 身着红色紧身连衣裙、走路时臀部来回轻微扭动的女人

value.def: If something swings in a particular direction or if you swing it in that direction, it moves in that direction with a smooth, curving movement.

example.ex: The torchlight swung across the little beach and out over the water, searching...
example.tran: 手电筒的光在小海滩上扫过，而后照向水面搜索着。

example.ex: The canoe found the current and swung around...
example.tran: 独木舟遇上急流后直打转。

example.ex: Roy swung his legs carefully off the couch and sat up.
example.tran: 罗伊小心地把腿挪下沙发，坐了起来。

example.ex: When he's not on the tennis court, you'll find him practising his golf swing.
example.tran: 他不打网球时就练习高尔夫挥杆。

value.tran: (使)成弧线运动;(使)转动;(使)转弯

value.def: If a vehicle swings in a particular direction, or if the driver swings it in a particular direction, they turn suddenly in that direction.

example.ex: Joanna swung back on to the main approach and headed for the airport...
example.tran: 乔安娜猛地调转车头回到主路上，朝机场开去。

example.ex: The tyres dug into the grit as he swung the car off the road.
example.tran: 当他一个急转弯把车驶离马路时，轮胎陷进了沙子里。

value.def: If someone swings around, they turn around quickly, usually because they are surprised.

example.ex: She swung around to him, spilling her tea without noticing it.
example.tran: 她一下子转身面向他，茶水溅了出来都没注意到。

value.def: If you swing at a person or thing, you try to hit them with your arm or with something that you are holding.

example.ex: Blanche swung at her but she moved her head back and Blanche missed...
example.tran: 布兰奇挥手朝她打去，但她头向后一闪，布兰奇没有打到。

example.ex: I picked up his baseball bat and swung at the man's head.
example.tran: 我捡起他的棒球棒朝那个人的头打去。

example.ex: I often want to take a swing at someone to relieve my feelings.
example.tran: 我常想打谁一顿来发泄情感。

value.tran: (挥动手臂等)朝…打去;朝…挥击;挥向

value.def: A swing is a seat hanging by two ropes or chains from a metal frame or from the branch of a tree. You can sit on the seat and move forwards and backwards through the air.
Swing is a style of jazz dance music that was popular in the 1930's. It was played by big bands.
value.tran: 摇摆乐(流行于 20 世纪 30 年代的爵士舞曲)

value.def: A swing in people's opinions, attitudes, or feelings is a change in them, especially a sudden or big change.

example.ex: There was a massive twenty per cent swing away from the Conservatives to the Liberal Democrats...
example.tran: 出现了一个巨大转变:多达20％的人由支持保守党转而支持自由民主党。

example.ex: Educational practice is liable to sudden swings and changes...
example.tran: 教学实践中经常会出现突然的变化与改革。

example.ex: Dieters suffer from violent mood swings.
example.tran: 节食者会有激烈的情绪波动。

value.tran: (意见、态度或感情的)改变;(尤指)突变，巨变

value.def: If people's opinions, attitudes, or feelings swing, they change, especially in a sudden or extreme way.

example.ex: In two years' time there is a presidential election, and the voters could swing again...
example.tran: 总统选举在两年后举行，届时选民们可能会再次倒向另一方。

example.ex: The mood amongst Tory MPs seems to be swinging away from their leader.
example.tran: 保守党议员似乎正在疏远他们的领袖。

value.tran: (意见、态度或感情)改变;(尤指)突然转变，完全改变

value.def: If someone such as a politician makes a swing through a particular country or area, they go on a quick trip through it, visiting a number of different places.

example.ex: ...a campaign swing through South Dakota and Texas.
example.tran: 在南达科他州和得克萨斯州的巡回竞选活动

value.def: If something is in full swing, it is operating fully and is no longer in its early stages.

example.ex: When we returned, the party was in full swing and the dance floor was crowded...
example.tran: 我们回来时，聚会已进入高潮，舞池里挤满了人。

example.ex: The international rugby season is in full swing.
example.tran: 国际橄榄球赛季正如火如荼地进行着。

value.tran: 在热烈进行中;处于兴盛阶段

value.def: If you get into the swing of something, you become very involved in it and enjoy what you are doing.

example.ex: Everyone understood how hard it was to get back into the swing of things after such a long absence.
example.tran: 每个人都知道这么长时间不在，再重新完全融入进来有多难。

value.tran: 融入;完全投入;对…乐在其中

value.def: If you say that something is going with a swing, you mean that it is lively and exciting.

example.ex: Sara Lewis' impressive recipes are guaranteed to make the party go with a swing.
example.tran: 萨拉·刘易斯令人赞不绝口的食谱一定能使聚会的气氛热烈非凡。

value.def: If you say that a situation is swings and roundabouts, you mean that there are as many gains as there are losses.
